---
import RoomLayout from '../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';
---

<RoomLayout
  room="reading"
  title="Reading Room"
  subtitle="The Library's reference shelf — five sections, layered together."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="reading-toc"
>
  <section class="reading-room mt-6">
    <p class="reading-frame">
      The Reading Room is the Library's reference shelf. Five sections layered
      together: the Library's own argument about America's school trust lands; the
      period primary sources the framers and reformers actually wrote; the secondary
      scholarship that has tried to make sense of those records; the state-by-state
      primary-source corners curated by State Co-Librarians; and signed editorial
      voices from the wider community. Most of it is open to the public domain;
      the rest is mapped for you to find at a library near you.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <!-- I. The Library's Argument                                          -->
    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <section class="reading-section" id="library-argument">
      <header class="reading-section-header">
        <h2>I. The Library's Argument</h2>
        <p class="reading-section-purpose">
          The Library's own published synthesis: how the school-trust system was
          designed, how it has drifted across 240 years, and what the architects of
          the next century's intergenerational trusts should incorporate.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <img
            src="/img/covers/schools-of-the-republic-cover.jpg"
            alt="Schools of the Republic cover"
            onerror="this.style.display='none'; this.parentElement.classList.add('plss-pattern')"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Booklet · Sullivan and Bird · 2025</span>
          <h3>Schools of the Republic</h3>
          <div class="byline">A Ten-Chapter Synthesis on America's School Trust Lands · Substrate v1.3</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            A ten-chapter synthesis of America's school trust lands — from the 1785 Land
            Ordinance to the present, with the constitutional architecture, the doublings of
            the antebellum and Reconstruction eras, the twentieth-century high-water mark, the
            modern drift, and the captured-Attorney-General enforcement architecture that
            requires a standing constituency to remedy.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>Table of contents</summary>
            <ol class="numbered-toc">
              <li><a href="/reading/prologue/">Prologue</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/founding-floor/">The Founding Floor — 1785, the Land Ordinance, and the school clause</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/statehood-without-federal-floor/">Statehood Without a Federal Floor — the Original 13 and the eastern path</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/northwest-ordinance-template/">The Northwest Ordinance Template — Section 16 enters the federal-grant statehood compact</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/antebellum-doubling/">Antebellum Doubling — California, Oregon, and the doubled grant</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/reconstruction-western-stack/">The Reconstruction Western Stack — the post-1867 admissions and the railroad-era pressures</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/twentieth-century-high-water-mark/">The Twentieth-Century High-Water Mark — fund growth and stewardship intervals</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/comparative-atlas/">Comparative Atlas — what fifty states reveal at a glance</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/enforcement-beneficiary-cannot-sue/">Enforcement When the Beneficiary Cannot Sue — the captured-AG architecture and the eighth anchor</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/conclusion/">Conclusion — what the trusts ask of us now</a></li>
            </ol>
          </details>
          <a href="/reading/schools-of-the-republic/" class="cta">Read the booklet</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <img
            src="/img/covers/sacred-compact-cover.jpg"
            alt="Sacred Compact cover"
            onerror="this.style.display='none'; this.parentElement.classList.add('plss-pattern')"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">White paper · 70 pages</span>
          <h3>The Sacred Compact</h3>
          <div class="byline">
            Dave Sullivan and Margaret Bird · v5.0 (May 2026) · 207 footnotes
          </div>
          <p class="abstract">
            America wrote a 250-year intergenerational trust into the geometry of the
            country in 1785, and the experiment has now returned its data. <em>The Sacred
            Compact</em> is the analytic frame: how the system was designed to outlast its
            founders, what drift and directed seizure look like in practice across all
            fifty states, the seven structural anchors and the eighth that hold against
            them, and what the architects of the next century's perpetual trusts —
            climate trusts, sovereign wealth for the unborn, AI governance authorities —
            should incorporate before they commit.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>Table of contents</summary>
            <ol>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-prologue/">Prologue — A Forever Gift</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-i-the-question/">I. The Question — what an aspirational structure must do to outlast its founders</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-ii-the-sacred-compact/">II. The Sacred Compact — the founding moment, 1785 to the early statehoods</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-iii-the-drift/">III. The Drift — what fiduciary breach looks like in practice, from California to Nebraska</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-iv-the-pattern/">IV. The Pattern — the four faces of drift and the structure of directed seizure</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-v-the-counter-architecture/">V. The Counter-Architecture — the seven pillars and the eighth anchor</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-vi-the-coming-trusts/">VI. The Coming Trusts — climate, AI, sovereign wealth, and the architectures the next century will inherit</a></li>
              <li><a href="/reading/sacred-compact-vii-civic-practice/">VII. A Civic Practice — what each readership can do with the historical evidence</a></li>
            </ol>
          </details>
          <a href="/reading/sacred-compact-prologue/" class="cta">Read the paper</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Entry-door read · 60 seconds</span>
          <h3>Why this matters</h3>
          <div class="byline">A 60-second on-ramp to the Library's argument</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            The single-page version of why the school-trust experiment is the only
            multi-generational evidence the world has on how perpetual fiduciary
            structures behave under generational pressure — and why it matters
            for the architects of the next century's perpetual trusts.
          </p>
          <a href="/why/" class="cta">Read the entry-door page →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <p class="reading-section-footer">
        <a href="/contribute/">Suggest a contribution →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <!-- II. The Founders' Library                                          -->
    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <section class="reading-section" id="founders-library">
      <header class="reading-section-header">
        <h2>II. The Founders' Library</h2>
        <p class="reading-section-purpose">
          Period primary sources, organized by era, that show what the framers and
          reformers actually wrote about schools, lands, and trust architecture.
          Founding era, common-school era, and high-water/reform era — public-domain
          throughout.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Section II · 15 entries · public domain</span>
          <h3>The Founders' Library</h3>
          <div class="byline">Founding era (1779–1787) · Common-school era (1837–1879) · High-water and reform era (1904–present)</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Fifteen primary-source curated entry-points spanning the founding,
            common-school, and high-water/reform eras. The Land Ordinance of 1785 and
            the Northwest Ordinance of 1787; Federalist No. 10, the Massachusetts
            Constitution of 1780, and Jefferson's 1779 Bill for the Diffusion of
            Knowledge; Horace Mann, Henry Barnard, John Pierce, and the McGuffey
            Readers; Fitch and Skinner, Swift, Kiddle and Schem, Hawkes, and Utah
            Code Title 53C as the modern-reform anchor. Each entry is a one-page
            reader's frame with citations to the canonical source.
          </p>
          <a href="/reading/founders-library/" class="cta">Browse the Founders' Library →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <p class="reading-section-footer">
        <a href="/contribute/">Suggest a contribution →</a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="/contribute/state-lands-agencies/">State Co-Librarians: see /contribute/state-lands-agencies/ →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <!-- III. The Scholarship                                               -->
    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <section class="reading-section" id="scholarship">
      <header class="reading-section-header">
        <h2>III. The Scholarship</h2>
        <p class="reading-section-purpose">
          Secondary academic work on school trust lands, school finance, and trust
          law — what scholars say about what the framers said. Three tiers:
          public-domain older scholarship; open-access modern; in-copyright modern
          reference works (Title Steward — OPEN).
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Foundational · 1911</span>
          <h3>History of Public Permanent Common School Funds in the United States, 1795–1905</h3>
          <div class="byline">Fletcher Harper Swift · Columbia University · 1911</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            The seminal academic study of America's school trust funds. Comprehensive
            state-by-state accounting of permanent common school funds from inception through
            1905. Public domain. The standard reference; no comprehensive successor work has
            been published since.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>Read the source</summary>
            <p>
              Source page at
              <a href="/reading/sources/swift-1911/">/reading/sources/swift-1911/</a>;
              local PDF at
              <a href="/sources/historyofpublicp00swif.pdf">/sources/historyofpublicp00swif.pdf</a> (30&nbsp;MB).
              Original digitization on
              <a href="https://archive.org/details/historyofpublicp00swif" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Internet Archive</a>.
            </p>
          </details>
          <a href="/reading/sources/swift-1911/" class="cta">Read the source page</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Foundational · 1949</span>
          <h3>A History of the Irreducible School Fund in Oregon</h3>
          <div class="byline">Norman B. Hawk · University of Oregon · June 1949 (digitized 2018)</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Norman B. Hawk's 1949 University of Oregon doctoral thesis on the Oregon
            Irreducible School Fund. Foundational reference for the project's Oregon-specific
            case material.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>Read the source</summary>
            <p>
              Source page at
              <a href="/reading/sources/hawk-2018/">/reading/sources/hawk-2018/</a>;
              local PDF at
              <a href="/sources/hawk_09072018_final.pdf">/sources/hawk_09072018_final.pdf</a> (89&nbsp;MB).
            </p>
          </details>
          <a href="/reading/sources/hawk-2018/" class="cta">Read the source page</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Investigative · 1908</span>
          <h3>Looters of the Public Domain</h3>
          <div class="byline">S.A.D. Puter and Horace Stevens · 1908</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Contemporaneous account of the Oregon land-fraud trials of the early 1900s.
            Primary-source material on the Mitchell trial and the broader pattern of
            public-land grift in the West. Public domain. Available on Internet Archive.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>External source</summary>
            <p>
              Full text on
              <a
                href="https://archive.org/details/lootersofpublicd00puteuoft"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener"
                >Internet Archive</a>.
            </p>
          </details>
          <a
            href="https://archive.org/details/lootersofpublicd00puteuoft"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="cta">Read on Internet Archive →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Academic · 2014</span>
          <h3>Closing the Book on the School Trust Lands</h3>
          <div class="byline">Heidelberg · National Agricultural Law Center · 2014</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Recent academic analysis of state-level school trust lands accounting and reform
            pathways. Cites Swift 1911 as the seminal reference and updates with 21st-century
            data.
          </p>
          <details class="toc">
            <summary>External source</summary>
            <p>
              <a
                href="https://nationalaglawcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/assets/bibarticles/heidelberg_trust.pdf"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener"
                >National Agricultural Law Center</a>.
            </p>
          </details>
          <a
            href="https://nationalaglawcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/assets/bibarticles/heidelberg_trust.pdf"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="cta">Read the paper →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow tier3-eyebrow">Tier 3 · in-copyright · Title Steward — OPEN · 5 entries</span>
          <h3>Tier 3 — modern reference works (curator-recruitment open)</h3>
          <div class="byline">NEFA <em>Funding Public Schools</em> (2024) · Bogert · <em>Restatement (Third) of Trusts</em> · Souder &amp; Fairfax 1996 · Culp 2006</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Five in-copyright reference works the Library cannot host directly but
            wants to surface, recommend, and recruit a Title Steward to maintain.
            Each title currently has an open Title Steward seat.
          </p>
          <a href="/reading/scholarship/" class="cta">Browse the Scholarship section →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <p class="reading-section-footer">
        <a href="/contribute/">Suggest a contribution →</a>
        &nbsp;·&nbsp;
        <a href="/contribute/">Title Stewards welcome — see /contribute/ →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <!-- IV. State Records                                                  -->
    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <section class="reading-section" id="state-records">
      <header class="reading-section-header">
        <h2>IV. State Records</h2>
        <p class="reading-section-purpose">
          State-by-state primary-source corners curated by State Co-Librarians:
          enabling acts, constitutional education clauses, key state-court decisions,
          audit reports, AG opinions, reform-era statutes. Launching in scaffolded
          form. Oregon and Utah are the first exemplar corners; additional states
          open as State Co-Librarians take on curation.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Section IV · scaffolded · 17 state pages live</span>
          <h3>State Records — by state</h3>
          <div class="byline">Oregon and Utah are the bespoke exemplars; 15 additional states have full ASTL re-merge state pages.</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Browse per-state dossiers via the
            <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>. Two exemplar State Records corners are
            currently live as bespoke pages:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="/reading/us-or/">Oregon</a> — the live test case</li>
            <li><a href="/reading/us-ut/">Utah</a> — the recovery case</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="abstract">
            Open: 48 more states await State Co-Librarian curation. The Library is
            actively recruiting.
          </p>
          <a href="/contribute/state-lands-agencies/" class="cta">For state-lands-agency staff →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <p class="reading-section-footer">
        <a href="/contribute/state-lands-agencies/">State Co-Librarians: apply via /contribute/state-lands-agencies/ →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="archival-divider" />

    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <!-- V. Voices                                                          -->
    <!-- ================================================================== -->
    <section class="reading-section" id="voices">
      <header class="reading-section-header">
        <h2>V. Voices</h2>
        <p class="reading-section-purpose">
          Signed editorial pieces, op-eds, testimony, and beneficiary statements
          from the wider community. Different voice from the booklet — sharper,
          more present-tense, often a direct response to what trustees,
          legislators, or courts just did.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="reading-card">
        <div class="cover">
          <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="meta">
          <span class="eyebrow">Section V · ASTL contributors</span>
          <h3>Voices</h3>
          <div class="byline">Seven ASTL contributors at launch; expanding through Newsroom-affiliated essays and beneficiary-voice submissions.</div>
          <p class="abstract">
            Voices articles originate at
            <a href="https://www.schooltrustlands.org/astl-voices" target="_blank" rel="noopener">schooltrustlands.org/astl-voices</a>
            and are reproduced here as part of the Library's evidentiary archive.
            Each article is signed by its author and dated.
          </p>
          <a href="/voices/" class="cta">Browse Voices →</a>
        </div>
      </article>

      <p class="reading-section-footer">
        <a href="/contribute/">Submit a piece →</a>
      </p>
    </section>

  </section>

  <style>
    .reading-frame {
      font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
      font-size: 1.05rem;
      line-height: 1.65;
      color: #334155;
      margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .reading-section {
      margin-top: 2rem;
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }
    .reading-section-header h2 {
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
    }
    .reading-section-purpose {
      font-style: italic;
      color: #475569;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.55;
      margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    }
    .reading-section-footer {
      margin-top: 1rem;
      font-size: 0.9rem;
      color: #475569;
    }
    .tier3-eyebrow {
      color: #b45309 !important; /* amber-700 */
    }
  </style>
</RoomLayout>
